<section id="wildlife">
  <h2>Wildlife Observations</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Type:</strong> Mammal, Reptile, Bird, Fish, or Insect</li>
    <li><strong>Bird Call:</strong> Submit audio recording</li>
    <li><strong>Wildlife Notes:</strong> Freeform text field for additional details (behavior, habitat, number of individuals, etc.)</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Native Wildlife by Category</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Mammals:</strong> North American Beaver, River Otter, Black-tailed Deer</li>
    <li><strong>Birds:</strong> Great Blue Heron, Belted Kingfisher, Red-tailed Hawk, American Dipper</li>
    <li><strong>Fish:</strong> Chinook Salmon, Coho Salmon, Cutthroat Trout, Pacific Lamprey</li>
    <li><strong>Reptiles:</strong> Northwestern Garter Snake, Western Pond Turtle</li>
    <li><strong>Insects:</strong> Western Tiger Swallowtail, Green Darner Dragonfly</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Invasive Wildlife by Category</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Mammals:</strong> Nutria</li>
    <li><strong>Birds:</strong> European Starling, House Sparrow</li>
    <li><strong>Fish:</strong> Common Carp, Smallmouth Bass</li>
    <li><strong>Reptiles:</strong> Red-eared Slider</li>
    <li><strong>Insects:</strong> European Paper Wasp, Japanese Beetle</li>
  </ul>
</section>
<section id="plants">
  <h2>Plant Observations</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Plant Type:</strong> Invasive, Non-invasive</li>
    <li><strong>Plant Category:</strong> Trees, Shrubs, Grass, Wildflowers</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Native Species by Category</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Trees:</strong> Red Alder, Oregon White Oak, Bigleaf Maple, Douglas-fir, Black Cottonwood, Pacific Willow, Western Redcedar, Oregon Ash</li>
    <li><strong>Shrubs:</strong> Red-osier Dogwood, Snowberry, Salmonberry, Thimbleberry, Oceanspray, Nootka Rose</li>
    <li><strong>Grasses:</strong> Slough Sedge, Tufted Hairgrass, Common Rush, Douglas' Aster, Yarrow</li>
    <li><strong>Wildflowers:</strong> Camas, Western Trillium, Monkeyflower, Skunk Cabbage</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Invasive Species by Category</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Trees:</strong> None commonly noted in the Tualatin riparian corridor</li>
    <li><strong>Shrubs:</strong> Himalayan Blackberry, Spurge Laurel</li>
    <li><strong>Grasses:</strong> Lesser Celandine, Yellow Archangel</li>
    <li><strong>Wildflowers:</strong> Garlic Mustard, Japanese Knotweed, Policeman’s Helmet, Purple Loosestrife, Yellowflag Iris, Jewelweed</li>
    <li><strong>Vines:</strong> English Ivy, Traveler’s Joy</li>
  </ul>
</section>
<section id="altered">
  <h2>Altered Agricultural Practice</h2>
  <p>An open-ended notes field is provided for describing observed land use changes such as plowing too close to the waterway, livestock runoff, or crop residue dumping.</p>
</section>
<section id="erosion">
  <h2>Riverbank Erosion</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Bank:</strong> North or South</li>
    <li><strong>Severity:</strong> Minor, Moderate, or Severe</li>
    <li><strong>Vegetation Cover:</strong> Sparse, Moderate, or Dense</li>
    <li><strong>Estimated Age:</strong> New, Recent, or Old</li>
    <li><strong>Notes:</strong> Optional text box for observations</li>
  </ul>
</section>
<section id="logjams">
  <h2>Log Jams or Blockages</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Size:</strong> Small, Medium, or Large</li>
    <li><strong>Flow Impact:</strong> Minor, Moderate, or Major</li>
    <li><strong>Visibility:</strong> Not Visible, Partially Visible, or Mostly Visible</li>
    <li><strong>Estimated Age:</strong> New, Recent, or Old</li>
  </ul>
</section>
<section id="water">
  <h2>Unusual Water Conditions</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Condition:</strong> Murky, Oily, Foamy, Discolored, Smelly, or Other</li>
    <li><strong>Notes:</strong> Optional description field for turbidity, effluent, or any other concern</li>
  </ul>
</section>
<section id="trash">
  <h2>Trash or Dumping</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Amount:</strong> Single item, Small pile, or Large pile</li>
    <li><strong>Type:</strong> Household, Construction, Agricultural, or Unknown</li>
    <li><strong>Location:</strong> On Land or In River</li>
  </ul>
</section>
<section id="other">
  <h2>Other</h2>
  <p>Users can describe any observation that doesn’t fall under the predefined categories. This supports unanticipated or rare events.</p>
</section>
